    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A U.S. Gas Tax To Help Iraq?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Betsy Albright letter on Thomas L Friedman's Oct 5 column lauds his call for $1-a-gallon gasoline tax to raise money for rebuilding Iraq</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Real Patriot Act'' (column, Oct. 5):</p>
        <p>I applaud Thomas L. Friedman's proposal for a $1-a-gallon gasoline tax to raise money for the Iraq reconstruction.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Real Patriot Act'' (column, Oct. 5):</p>
        <p>I applaud Thomas L. Friedman's proposal for a $1-a-gallon gasoline tax to raise money for the Iraq reconstruction.</p>
        <p>Because of market failures, the current price of gasoline in the United States improperly excludes externalities created by its consumption: localized air pollution, environmental damage from oil drilling, global climate change and American military and foreign policy developed to protect our interests in oil-producing nations.</p>
        <p>In addition, proper pricing of gasoline would provide an incentive for the development of alternative energy sources.</p>
        <p>By adjusting our current prices of gasoline to account for these externalities, not only would we be paying for the true cost of gasoline, we would improve our standing in the world.</p>
        <p>BETSY ALBRIGHT  Durham, N.C., Oct. 5, 2003</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
